06968nam a22010455i 9780812207323DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20122013pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979756587  a97808122073237 a10.9783/97808122073232doi  a(DE-B1597)449642  a(OCoLC)823710309  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aARC0080002bisacsh04a635.90942  aZH 97302rvk0(DE-625)rvk/156331:158104aThe Pleasure Garden, from Vauxhall to Coney Island /ced. by Jonathan Conlin. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2012] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b73 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPenn Studies in Landscape Architecture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Theaters of Hospitality: The Forms and Uses of Private Landscapes and Public Gardens -- tChapter 2. Pleasure Gardens and Urban Culture in the Long Eighteenth Century -- tChapter 3. Guns in the Gardens: Peter Monamy’s Paintings for Vauxhall -- tChapter 4. Performance Alfresco: Music-Making in London’s Pleasure Gardens -- tChapter 5. Pleasure Gardens of America: Anxieties of National Identity -- tChapter 6. Pleasure Gardens in Nineteenth-Century New Orleans: ‘‘Useful for All Classes of Society’’ -- tChapter 7. Night and Day: Illusion and Carnivalesque at Vauxhall -- tChapter 8. ‘‘Strange Beauty in the Night’’: Whistler’s Nocturnes of Cremorne Gardens -- tChapter 9. Edwardian Amusement Parks: The Pleasure Garden Reborn? -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSummers at the Vauxhall pleasure garden in London brought diverse entertainments to a diverse public. Picturesque walks and arbors offered a pastoral retreat from the city, while at the same time the garden's attractions indulged distinctly urban tastes for fashion, novelty, and sociability. High- and low-born alike were free to walk the paths; the proximity to strangers and the danger of dark walks were as thrilling to visitors as the fountains and fireworks. Vauxhall was the venue that made the careers of composers, inspired novelists, and showcased the work of artists. Scoundrels, sudden downpours, and extortionate ham prices notwithstanding, Vauxhall became a must-see destination for both Londoners and tourists. Before long, there were Vauxhalls across Britain and America, from York to New York, Norwich to New Orleans.This edited volume provides the first book-length study of the attractions and interactions of the pleasure garden, from the opening of Vauxhall in the seventeenth century to the amusement parks of the early twentieth. Nine essays explore the mutual influences of human behavior and design: landscape, painting, sculpture, and even transient elements such as lighting and music tacitly informed visitors how to move within the space, what to wear, how to behave, and where they might transgress. The Pleasure Garden, from Vauxhall to Coney Island draws together the work of musicologists, art historians, and scholars of urban studies and landscape design to unfold a cultural history of pleasure gardens, from the entertainments they offered to the anxieties of social difference they provoked.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAmusementszEnglandxHistory. 0aAmusementszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aGardensxSocial aspectszEnglandxHistory. 0aGardensxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aGardensxSocial aspects. 0aResortszEnglandxHistory. 0aResortszUnited StatesxHistory. 4aArchitecture. 7aARCHITECTURE / Landscape.2bisacsh  aArchitecture.  aCultural Studies.  aEuropean History.  aFine Art.  aGarden History.  aWorld History.1 aBorsay,